definition.value: Any dihydroflavonol that has 2R,3R-configuration.
A trienoic fatty acid that is (6E,8Z,11Z)-icosatrienoic acid carrying an additional oxo substituent at position 5.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of any 3'-end 3'-(N-acyl-L-alpha-aminoacyl)adenylyl residue; major species at pH 7.3.

A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-beflubutamid. An inhibitor of carotenoid biosynthesis, it is used for the pre- and early post-emergence control of broad-leaved weeds in a variety of cereal crops. The (-)-enantiomer has at least 1000 times higher herbicidal activity than the (+)-enantiomer.
A diamino acid that is hexanoic acid carrying two amino substituents at positions 2 and 5 (the 2R,5S-diastereomer).
A phosphatidylcholine 12:0 in which both acyl groups are specified as hexanoyl.
A phosphatidylcholine 14:0 in which both acyl groups are specified as heptanoyl.
A leukotriene that is leukotriene B4 carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 19.
A 1-hexanoyl-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group at position 2 is specified as heptanoyl.
A phosphatidylcholine 13:0 in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as heptanoyl and hexanoyl respectively.
1-palmitoyl-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 2-acyl group is specified as heptanoyl.
1-acyl-2-palmitoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 1-acyl group is specified as heptanoyl.
A leukotriene that is leukotriene B4 carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 18.
A docosanoid that is (14S)-hydroxy-(4Z,7Z,9E,11E,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoic acid in which a glutathionyl group is attached at position 13R via a sulfide linkage.
A monocarboxylic acid amide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 2-[4-fluoro-3-(trifluoromethyl)phenoxy]butyric acid with the amino group of benzylamine.
An N-benzyl-2-[4-fluoro-3-(trifluoromethyl)phenoxy]butanamide that has R configuration.
An N-benzyl-2-[4-fluoro-3-(trifluoromethyl)phenoxy]butanamide that has S configuration.
A docosanoid that is (14S)-hydroxy-(4Z,7Z,9E,11E,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoic acid in which a cysteinylglycinyl group is attached at position 13R via a sulfide linkage.
A linear amino trisaccharide consisting of N-acetyl-beta-Dglucosamine, alpha-D-galactose and D-galactose residues joined in sequence by (1->4) and (1->3)linkages respectively.
Any pathway inhibitor that acts on the carotenoid biosynthesis pathway.
A docosanoid that is (14S)-hydroxy-(4Z,7Z,9E,11E,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoic acid in which a cysteinyl group is attached at position 13R via a sulfide linkage.
An amino disaccharide composed of N-acetyl-D-glucosamine and D-galactose residues in a beta(1->4) linkage.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as octadecanoyl and pentanoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 24:0 in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as octadecanoyl and hexanoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 26:0 in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as octadecanoyl and octanoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 27:0 in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as octadecanoyl and nonanoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 30:0 in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as octadecanoyl and dodecananoyl respectively.
1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as hexanoyl.
1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as heptanoyl and hexanoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylethanolamine 34:0 zwitterion in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as heptadecanoyl.
A diterpene that is the enantiomer of atisane which has undergone formal dehydrogenation to indroduce an exocyclic double bond at position 16.
An N-hexadecanoylphosphatidylethanolamine(1-) in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as heptadecanoyl.
A CDP-sugar having D-ribulose as the sugar component with the CDP moiety attached at position 5.
An N-oleoylphosphatidylethanolamine(1-) in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as heptadecanoyl.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of ent-copal-8-ol diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A tricyclic diterpenoid that is isolated from plants and fungi and exhibits anti-bacterial protperties.
A CDP-sugar having aldehydo-D-ribose as the sugar component with the CDP moiety attached at position 5.
A sesterterpene that is beta-farnesene in which one of the terminal methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a geranyl group.
An acyclic triterpene that is 3-methylidenetetracosa-1,6,10,14,18,22-hexaene carrying five methyl substituents at positions 7, 11, 15, 19 and 23 (the all-E geoisomer).
An acyclic sesquarterpene that is 3-methylideneoctacosa-1,6,10,14,18,22,26-heptaene carrying six methyl substituents at positions 7, 11, 15, 19, 23 and 27 (the all-E geoisomer).
A member of the class of muramic acids that is N-acetyl-alpha-D-muramic acid in which the anomeric hydroxy hydrogen has been replaced by a phospho group.
Any of the O-polysaccharides present as part of the lipopolysaccharides of Burkholderia species.

An O-polysaccharide consisting of repeating 1,3-linked 6-deoxy-alpha-L-talosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-glucosyl units; it forms the O-antigen repeat section of one of the lipopolysaccharides of Burkholderia pseudomallei and/or Burkholderia mallei, the etiologic agents of melioidosis and glanders, respectively.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of peregrinol diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A tricyclic diterpenoid that is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of marrubiin by the medicinal plant Marrubium vulgare.
A tricyclic labdane diterpenoid that is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of forskolin by Coleus forskohlii.
An organic heteropentacyclic compound and ent-kaurane diterpenoid with formula C20H28O6 isolated from the leaves of the medicinal herb Rabdosia rubescens.
A member of the class of pteroic acids that is 7,8-dihydropteroic acid carrying a phenolic hydroxy substituent at the position ortho to the carboxylic acid function.
A nucleoside 5'-monophosphate(2-) obtained by deprotonation of the phospohate OH groups of any pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
